## Common MacBook Logic Board Faults We See in Johannesburg

### 1. No Power — MacBook Will Not Turn On

This is the most common complaint we receive. The cause can range from a failed power delivery IC, a blown fuse, a shorted capacitor, or a faulty battery management circuit. In most cases, component-level repair resolves this without a board replacement.

### 2. USB-C Charging Failures

On modern MacBook Pro and MacBook Air models, charging is managed through USB-C Power Delivery controllers. These small ICs are vulnerable to power surges (a very real problem in South Africa given our unstable grid and load shedding-related power fluctuations). We regularly replace CD3215 and other USB-C controller chips at component level.

### 3. GPU and Display Faults

Random screen flickering, graphical distortion, or a MacBook that starts up but displays nothing on the screen often points to a GPU fault. On certain Intel-era MacBook Pro models (particularly the 2011–2013 range), GPU failures were so common that Apple acknowledged them through a repair programme. We continue to see these faults and address them through reflow, underfill removal, and chip replacement.

### 4. Liquid Damage Corrosion

Spilling water, coffee, or a soft drink on a MacBook can cause corrosion to spread across the logic board within hours. [Liquid damage repair](/liquid-damage) requires thorough ultrasonic cleaning, corrosion removal under magnification, trace repair, and component replacement — all of which fall within our microsoldering capability. Acting quickly dramatically improves outcomes; the longer corrosion sits, the more board area it affects.

### 5. Random Shutdowns and Kernel Panics

If your MacBook shuts down without warning, often accompanied by a kernel panic report, the fault may lie in power management, RAM, or a failing voltage regulator on the board. Diagnostic software combined with physical inspection under our microscope usually isolates the fault efficiently.

